<subSubSection id="D9F16554FF93BA3FB4BBFF66B325F70B" pageId="47" pageNumber="666" type="activity">
<paragraph id="915436DFFF93BA3FB4BBFF66B325F70B" blockId="47.[169,1379,1234,2561]" pageId="47" pageNumber="666">
<emphasis id="A39FEACDFF93BA3FB4BBFF66B3B2F7E9" bold="true" box="[169,404,2054,2087]" pageId="47" pageNumber="666">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The African Giant Free-tailed Bat is nocturnal. Specimens have been caught emerging from the roofs of houses, and one was collected from a high-rise building in 
<collectingRegion id="532FF83DFF93BA3FB542FF35B393F7B8" box="[336,437,2133,2166]" country="Zimbabwe" name="Harare" pageId="47" pageNumber="666">Harare</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="E9FC764FFF93BA3FB5D7FF35B07EF7B8" box="[453,600,2133,2166]" name="Zimbabwe" pageId="47" pageNumber="666">Zimbabwe</collectingCountry>
. The species produces echolocation calls with low peak frequency (c.19 kHz), narrow bandwidth (c.4 kHz), and long duration (c.9 milliseconds).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
